"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753615","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-25","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-25T13:43:22.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753615/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753615/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-18","Personal Independence Payment: Neath","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the number and proportion is of people in Neath constituency who were categorised as lifelong recipients of disability living allowance and who were subsequently judged ineligible to receive personal independence payments in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","5861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753616","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-25","<p>The department does not hold the required information on point scores at appeal. We therefore cannot provide the average difference in points awarded at initial assessment and on appeal for those who claim personal independence payment following an appeal.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-25T13:37:58.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753616/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753616/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-18","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average difference is in points awarded at initial assessment and on appeal for those who claim personal independence payment following an appeal.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","5856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753617","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-26","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the answer I gave on 18 July 2017 to question 4898</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-26T11:43:29.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753617/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753617/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-18","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 3 July 2017 to Question 1063, if he will make it his policy to record the data necessary to calculate the average time between universal credit applicants making their initial application and receiving their first payment; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","5940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753618","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-26","<p>The Government’s National Action Plan on Business and Human Rights implements the United Nations’ voluntary Guiding Principles and sets out expectations of businesses to respect human rights wherever they operate. As part of this, businesses are encouraged to adopt appropriate due diligence policies to identify, prevent and mitigate human rights risks and to consult people who may be affected at all stages of project design and implementation, in ways which ensure their participation and take into account language or other potential barriers, and to pay particular attention to indigenous peoples. The Government’s Overseas Business Risk service helps with this by providing geopolitical and economic analysis on overseas markets to exporters, including information on potential human rights risks.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-26T08:55:42.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753618/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753618/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Overseas Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government takes to ensure that British businesses abroad uphold (a) international law on free, prior and informed consent, (b) the International Labour Organisation Convention 169 on Indigenous and Tribal Peoples and the UN Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples and (c) the rights of land and environmental activists operational in other countries.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","5939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753619","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-24","<p>Ofgem is considering options to protect vulnerable consumers and has yet to announce a formal proposal. Alongside this Ofgem has announced a package of measures to help consumers move away from poor value tariffs.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-24T13:39:48.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753619/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753619/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Energy: Neath","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent estimate he has made of the number and proportion of constituents in Neath who will be covered by the Government's proposal to safeguard customers on the poorest-value energy tariffs.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","5862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753620","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-25","<p>This Government wants the UK to be the go-to place for researchers, innovators and investors across the world, and we intend to secure the right outcome for the UK research base as we exit the European Union.</p><p>As my Rt Hon. Friend the Prime Minister has said, we would welcome an agreement to continue to collaborate with our European partners on major science, research, and technology initiatives. However it is too early to speculate on the UK’s future relationship with the EU Research and Innovation Framework Programme, which includes the European Research Council.</p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring the UK remains a world leader in international research and innovation.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-25T16:19:24.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753620/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753620/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","European Research Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans the Government has for the relationship between the UK and the European Research Council after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","5707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753621","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Department will be publishing the Pye Tait research alongside a consultation document on the practice of cash retentions under construction shortly.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-05T14:33:49.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753621/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753621/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Construction: Payment Methods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when his Department plans to publish the (a) Pye Tait research and (b) consultation documents on the practice of cash retentions.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","5691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753622","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-26","<p>Job titles are determined by the needs of the business and the role being carried out to meet department and ministerial objectives. As a result this level of detail is not held centrally and to collate it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-26T15:58:38.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753622/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753622/answer","Question 5733 - agency responses.pdf","Question 5733 - agency responses.pdf","Agency responses","Agency responses","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753622/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many officials of his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public body have the word trade in their job title.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","5733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753623","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government published its response to the Green Paper consultation on Corporate Governance Reform on 29 August 2017.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of the response can be found:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/640631/corporate-governance-reform-government-response.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/640631/corporate-governance-reform-government-response.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-05T14:27:46.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753623/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753623/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when the Government plans to publish its response to the Corporate Governance Reform consultation.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","5678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753624","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-05","<p>Research and development is an important driver of productivity and growth both nationally and locally. The Government’s Industrial Strategy identified a range of other factors that also contribute to growth including skills, trade and inward investment, infrastructure, business support and sectors. The Government recognises that different places have different needs. Science and Innovation Audits are helping to develop the evidence base of where local research strength, innovation capability and potential markets are aligned. These audits are an important contribution to understanding of the strengths and opportunities of different regions as the Government develops an Industrial Strategy that works for all parts of the country.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","5680","2017-09-05T14:35:54.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753624/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753624/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has made an assessment of the effect of the distribution of research and development establishments on regional inequality.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","5679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753625","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-05","<p>Research and development is an important driver of productivity and growth both nationally and locally. The Government’s Industrial Strategy identified a range of other factors that also contribute to growth including skills, trade and inward investment, infrastructure, business support and sectors. The Government recognises that different places have different needs. Science and Innovation Audits are helping to develop the evidence base of where local research strength, innovation capability and potential markets are aligned. These audits are an important contribution to understanding of the strengths and opportunities of different regions as the Government develops an Industrial Strategy that works for all parts of the country.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","5679","2017-09-05T14:35:54.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753625/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753625/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will review ways of allocating Government investment in research and development to ensure regional equality.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","5680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753626","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-05","<p>It is right that Government supports sectors across the country to grow, invest and reach their potential. This is why we have invited British business to come forward with proposals for sector deals to advance the productivity of their particular sectors.</p><p> </p><p>Sector led proposals should be consistent with our Industrial Strategy and should demonstrate how they have been developed in partnership with local partners in key areas of competitive advantage for the specific sector across the country.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-05T15:21:26.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753626/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753626/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department has made an assessment of the effect of a sectoral approach to industrial strategy on regional inequality.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","5681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753627","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-26","<p>We are aware of the need to provide industry with clarity on the Renewable Heat Incentive reforms, and will do so as soon as possible.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-07-26T08:56:50.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753627/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753627/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to re-introduce the Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme Regulations 2017.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","5660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753628","Department for Education","false","2017-07-26","<p>The value of reserves held by each Further Education College or Sixth Form College in the East Midlands is shown in the attached table for the period 2009/10 to 2015/16, which is the latest college information available. The data also includes information from colleges that were dissolved during this period, following mergers with other colleges (highlighted in red).</p><p> </p><p>For the purpose of the information provided, the level of financial reserves is defined as the total net assets/(liabilities) and includes all assets/liabilities including pension liabilities.</p><p> </p><p>The 2015/16 college accounts were the first set of college financial statements produced under the requirements of the Statement of Recommended Practice: Accounting for Further and Higher Education (SORP2015). This update from SORP2007 reflected changes in the underlying accounting standards. Due to the changes in accounting standards a comparison between the 2015/16 reserves totals and the results from previous years is not a fair comparison.</p><p> </p><p>The source of the data is the college accounts annual datasets, which are published at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sfa-financial-management-college-accounts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sfa-financial-management-college-accounts</a></p><p>The datasets comprise the annual returns submitted to the Education and Skills Funding Agency (or predecessor bodies) by the respective individual colleges, which are then consolidated into one annual dataset.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-26T17:10:46.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753628/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753628/answer","5637 - attached table Final - 260717.pdf","5637 - attached table Final - 260717.pdf","Total College Reserves","Total College Reserves","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753628/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-18","Further Education: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what level of financial reserves were held by each further education establishment in the East Midlands at the end of each financial year from 2010 to the latest year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","5637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753629","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Investigations into takeovers are a matter for the Competition and Markets Authority, which are carried out under its statutory powers under the Enterprise Act 2002.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-21T10:44:10.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753629/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753629/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Tesco: Booker Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the implications for the Government's policies of the Competition and Markets Authority decision to hold an inquiry into the takeover of Booker by Tesco.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","5845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753630","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-26","<p>Last December, the Government issued updated guidance to public sector contracting authorities on how to ensure that they take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers when conducting their procurement activities. Since publication of the guidance, the Government has been working closely with central government departments, including the Department for Transport, to monitor the impact and effectiveness of the guidance.</p><p>The Government has also published details of upcoming steel requirements for national infrastructure projects. The data shows how the government plans to use three million tonnes of steel until 2020 on infrastructure projects such as High Speed 2 (HS2), the construction of Hinkley Point, and the maintenance and upgrading of the UK’s motorway network. This steel-specific pipeline complements the National Infrastructure and Construction Pipeline, which set out over £500 billion worth of planned private and public investment.</p><p>In order to maximise British involvement in supply chain opportunities in the construction of HS2, HS2 has engaged extensively with businesses of all sizes from a diverse range of sectors and across the UK; also working closely with UK Steel, British Constructional Steel Association, the Galvanisers Association and the Confederation of British Metalforming.</p><p>HS2 Ltd’s recently announced successful Main Works Contractor Tenderers have all confirmed they will comply with works information and further the requirements and spirit of HM Government Procurement Guidance on steel. HS2 will continue to engage with any British business that is interested in supporting its supply chain, throughout the lifetime of the programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-07-26T16:16:29.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753630/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753630/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with Secretary of State for Transport about the use of British-made steel in the construction of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","5846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753631","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-27","<p>National Insurance Contributions for self-employed people are a matter for Her Majesty’s Treasury.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-27T09:10:37.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753631/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753631/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","National Insurance Contributions: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 6 July 2017 to Question 2616, how much his Department spent on consultations with businesses and business organisations to seek views on proposed changes to national insurance contributions for self-employed people.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","5847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753632","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-21","<p>Food and drink is the UK’s largest manufacturing sector employing 400 000 people. The success of the industry is crucial to driving growth across the country.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to support the sector through raising the profile and reputation of British food and drink overseas through the Food is GREAT campaign. Defra and DIT are also opening new markets and supporting exports in priority markets such as China, USA and India. We are opening up public procurement to more SMEs and local producers and funding the Food Innovation Network to help the spread of innovation.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-07-21T16:04:26.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753632/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753632/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-18","Food: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 3 July 2017 to Question 1825, what financial support he plans to give to companies in the food manufacturing sector to secure jobs in the UK.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","5848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753633","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-26","<p>Food and drink is the UK’s largest manufacturing sector employing 400,000 people. The success of the industry is crucial to driving growth across the country. <br></p><p>Through our International Action Plan, Defra and DIT are helping the sector to export more. This is through opening new markets, supporting new exporters and targeted export campaigns in priority markets such as China, USA and India. We are opening up public procurement to more SMEs and local producers and funding the Food Innovation Network to help the spread of innovation.</p><p>There is extensive interest in the Industrial Strategy across the sector as evidenced by their response to the Industrial Strategy green paper. The sector is also keen on a sector deal and we look forward to seeing detailed proposals.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-07-26T13:20:20.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753633/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753633/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-18","Food: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to improve productivity in food manufacturing.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","5849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753634","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government will publish a response to the consultation in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-05T13:36:35.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753634/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753634/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to publish a response to the Post Office consultation that closed in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","5796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753635","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Feed-in Tariff scheme remains open and provides an incentive for small scale solar PV generators to invest in generating renewable electricity.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-09-05T15:23:05.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753635/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753635/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Solar Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on feed-in tariffs for solar energy.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","5840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753636","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-06","<p>Through the Advanced Propulsion Centre, the government has committed £500m over 10 years to accelerate the development of affordable low-carbon vehicle technologies that will form the basis of future vehicle supply chains, and maintain the international competitiveness of the UK automotive sector.</p><p>The Automotive Investment Organisation is leading government action to secure investment in manufacturing and R&amp;D facilities. This is central to increasing the level of local content in UK built vehicles, which increased to 44% in 2017, up from 36% in 2011.</p><p>The £246m Faraday Challenge, launched in July 2017, will ensure the UK leads the world in battery development.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-06T13:54:10.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753636/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753636/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753636/answer/previousversion/8438","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent investment the Government has made to support the supply chain for the automotive sector.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","5836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753637","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Techno-Economic Assessment of Small Modular Reactors (SMRs) was commissioned by the Government to help build the evidence base on SMRs. The report has helped the Government assess the contribution SMRs could make to the UK energy supply as well as identifying the benefits and risks of SMR deployment. The Government intends to publish the Techno-Economic Assessment in the autumn.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-09-05T16:22:28.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753637/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753637/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Nuclear Reactors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment he has made of the potential contribution of small modular nuclear reactors to UK energy supply.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","5791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753638","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-26","<p>The Department’s officials are currently developing options for an industrial energy efficiency scheme. I anticipate being in a position to provide more details on what such a scheme could look like in the coming months.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-07-26T16:17:16.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753638/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753638/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Industry: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to establish an industrial energy efficiency scheme.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","5782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753639","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-26","<p>Sir John Parker’s review is a business-led diversity initiative. He consulted on draft recommendations from November 2016 to February 2017, which the Government has endorsed.</p><p>Diversity and inclusion in the boardroom and the workplace is a hugely important element of building an economy that works for all. That is why I have created a Business Diversity and Inclusion Group to provide strategic leadership on this agenda, and to help deliver a clear and coordinated message to the business community on what they need to do. I have invited Sir John to participate alongside Sir Philip Hampton and Dame Helen Alexander, who are chairing a review aimed at increasing female leadership in FTSE companies, and Baroness Ruby McGregor-Smith, who led a review examining the obstacles faced by businesses in developing BME talent from recruitment through to the executive level.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will keep a close eye on how things develop and consider whether it needs to take further action once Sir John has finalised his recommendations later this year.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-26T15:46:46.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753639/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753639/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Ethnic Diversity of UK Boards Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent progress his Department has made on implementing the recommendations of the Parker Review on corporate boards.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","5711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753640","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-08-09","<p>It is anticipated that around two million tonnes of steel will be used across the HS2 programme. Last December, the Government issued updated guidance to public sector contracting authorities on how to ensure that they take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers when conducting their procurement activities.</p><p> </p><p>To maximise British involvement in supply chain opportunities HS2 has engaged extensively with businesses of all sizes from a diverse range of sectors and across the UK; also working closely with UK Steel, British Constructional Steel Association, the Galvanisers Association and the Confederation of British Metalforming.</p><p> </p><p>HS2 Ltd’s recently announced successful Main Works Contractor Tenderers have all confirmed they will comply with works information and further the requirements and spirit of HM Government Procurement Guidance on steel. HS2 will continue to engage with any British business that is interested in supporting its supply chain, throughout the lifetime of the programme.</p><p> </p><p>This level of detail builds upon the work this Government has achieved in publishing details of upcoming steel requirements for national infrastructure projects which shows how the Government plans to use three million tonnes of steel until 2020 on infrastructure projects such as High Speed 2 (HS2), the construction of Hinkley Point, and the maintenance and upgrading of the UK’s motorway network. This steel-specific pipeline complements the National Infrastructure and Construction Pipeline, which set out over £500 billion worth of planned private and public investment.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-08-09T09:22:29.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753640/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753640/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of how much steel required for the construction of High Speed 2 will be sourced in the UK.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","5783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753641","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-08-09","<p>We have commissioned independent research into future market opportunities for UK steel, which has involved substantial dialogue with existing and potential steel consumers across the whole of the UK. We are actively encouraging the UK steel sector to identify the capabilities it will need to act on the findings, and use this information to ensure they are well placed to plan and bid for future work.</p><p> </p><p>This is further complemented by the Government publishing details of upcoming steel requirements for national infrastructure projects which shows how the government plans to use three million tonnes of steel until 2020 on infrastructure projects such as High Speed 2 (HS2), the construction of Hinkley Point, and the maintenance and upgrading of the UK’s motorway network. This steel-specific pipeline further builds upon the National Infrastructure and Construction Pipeline, which set out over £500 billion worth of planned private and public investment; both which enable UK companies to anticipate material demand.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-08-09T09:24:27.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753641/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753641/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to encourage UK companies to buy British steel.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","5784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753642","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-08-09","<p>All of the procurement details specifically for HS2’s current and future pipeline of direct contracts are publically available via the HS2 Contract Opportunities Table, on the HS2 website. The HS2 Contracts Opportunity Table is a live document which is updated weekly, identifying the procurement status for each contract, including contact details to facilitate dialogue with potential bidders.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, this shows where organisations have been shortlisted and awarded, ensuring suppliers are appropriately informed regarding procurement and the programmes, and enabling sub Tier 1 contractors a direct access route into organisations that have been awarded work on the HS2 programme.</p><p> </p><p>This level of detail builds upon the Government’s published details of upcoming steel requirements for national infrastructure projects which shows how the Government plans to use three million tonnes of steel until 2020 on infrastructure projects such as High Speed 2 (HS2), the construction of Hinkley Point, and the maintenance and upgrading of the UK’s motorway network. This steel-specific pipeline complements the National Infrastructure and Construction Pipeline, which set out over £500 billion worth of planned private and public investment.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-08-09T09:26:36.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753642/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753642/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether pipeline data will be made available to UK steel producers who may wish to meet steel requirements for High Speed 2; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","5785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753643","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-26","<p>We are already taking steps to reduce the cost of energy for households and businesses and will outline our plans for the review shortly.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-26T10:29:48.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753643/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753643/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-18","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress has been made on commissioning an independent review into the cost of energy for households and businesses.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","5786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753644","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-26","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Arfon to the answer I gave on 24 July, UIN: 5029.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-07-26T11:20:24.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753644/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753644/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-18","Department for International Trade: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how much and what proportion of his Department's expenditure has been identified as relating to its work on the UK leaving the EU in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","5628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753645","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-26","<p>The Government has been clear that it wants to see zero tariffs on trade in goods and to minimise the regulatory and market access barriers for both goods and services. We want our deep and special partnership with the EU to include the automotive industry, ensuring that trade is as free and frictionless as possible.</p><p>It is in both our interests to continue this deep and special partnership between our industries, and we will secure a deal that works for the entire United Kingdom.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T16:50:00.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753645/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753645/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-18","UK Trade with EU: Motor Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will seek concessions on tariff-free trade with the EU for (a) the automotive industry and (b) Nissan in Sunderland after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","5640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753646","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>As set out clearly in the Government’s (Cm 9464) policy paper, free movement rights will come to an end after the UK leaves the EU and therefore cannot be carried forward, as an EU legal right, into the post-exit UK legal regime.</p><p> </p><p>Therefore all EU citizens (and their families) in the UK, regardless of when they arrived, will need to obtain an immigration status in UK law. As set out in the policy paper, EU citizens will be given adequate time to obtain this documentation through a ‘grace period’ of up to two years.</p><p> </p><p>While EU documentation certifying permanent residence will not be automatically replaced with a grant of settled status, we will seek to make the application process for settled status as streamlined as possible for those who already hold such documents. Fees and charges are being considered as part of the negotiations and in the Government’s engagement with stakeholders, but our aim is to keep fees at a reasonable level.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5694","2017-09-05T07:54:10.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753646/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753646/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether EU nationals who paid £65 for a document to prove permanent residency status will have to pay a fee to apply for settled status.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","5693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753647","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>As set out clearly in the Government’s (Cm 9464) policy paper, free movement rights will come to an end after the UK leaves the EU and therefore cannot be carried forward, as an EU legal right, into the post-exit UK legal regime.</p><p> </p><p>Therefore all EU citizens (and their families) in the UK, regardless of when they arrived, will need to obtain an immigration status in UK law. As set out in the policy paper, EU citizens will be given adequate time to obtain this documentation through a ‘grace period’ of up to two years.</p><p> </p><p>While EU documentation certifying permanent residence will not be automatically replaced with a grant of settled status, we will seek to make the application process for settled status as streamlined as possible for those who already hold such documents. Fees and charges are being considered as part of the negotiations and in the Government’s engagement with stakeholders, but our aim is to keep fees at a reasonable level.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5693","2017-09-05T07:54:10.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753647/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753647/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether those EU nationals who have successfully applied for a permanent residency document will need to apply for the new settled status to remain in the UK.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","5694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753648","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-26","<p>Officials working in a range of areas and professions have the word trade in their job title. The Department for Exiting the European Union’s published organisation chart can be found<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/609968/Untitled_presentation__2_.pdf" target="_blank"> here</a> and details the policy areas and teams within DExEU. This chart is kept under review and updated to reflect any structural changes.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T10:07:41.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753648/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753648/answer","DExEU organisational chart.pdf","DExEU organisational chart.pdf","DExEU organisational chart","DExEU organisational chart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753648/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-18","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many officials of his Department have the word trade in their job title.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","5738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753649","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-26","<p>The Government is considering the effect that exiting the EU will have on vulnerable children and young people across a wide range of issues. It is vital that these interests are heard as we enter the negotiations. Officials from the Department for Exiting the European Union have already engaged with child and youth advocacy groups and will continue to do so in the coming weeks and months as part of our strategy to ensure that a wide range of stakeholder perspectives are factored into our approach to exit.</p><p>The UK has a longstanding tradition of ensuring that our rights and liberties are protected domestically and of fulfilling our international human rights obligations. The decision to leave the EU does not change that. The Repeal Bill will ensure that our rights and freedoms will be brought into UK law and this includes the rights of vulnerable children and young people.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T12:04:18.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753649/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753649/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-18","Children and Young People: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, which policy areas relevant to vulnerable children and young people are under consideration in the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","5829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753650","Home Office","false","2017-07-25","<p>We intend to use the definition of continuous residence from Article 16(3) of the EU Free Movement Directive (2004/38/EC).</p><p>The Home Office will set out in due course what evidence may be provided as proof of continuous residence. We are committed to creating a streamlined and user-friendly applications system using existing government data to minimise the burden of documentary evidence required.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-25T15:08:51.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753650/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753650/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to paragraph 6 of her Department's policy paper entitled Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, how the term continuous in paragraph 27 is defined; and what proof of continuous residence will be required.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","5865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753651","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-31","<p>During negotiations and as part of a reciprocal deal, we are looking to protect the healthcare rights of both UK-insured individuals who are living in the EU and of EU-insured individuals who are living in the UK before the specified date.</p><p>The UK will seek to protect the reciprocal healthcare arrangements which enable UK residents to obtain a European Health Insurance Card, allowing them to benefit from free, or reduced cost, needs-arising healthcare while on a temporary stay in the EU.</p><p>The UK is also seeking to protect EU healthcare arrangements that enable those who have moved to the EU and continue to receive a UK benefit or draw a UK state pension to receive healthcare cover by the UK in their country of residence.</p><p>We will also seek to protect EU citizens’ eligibility for NHS funded healthcare in the UK and vice versa for UK nationals in the EU. Those who present valid documentation receive treatment on the NHS, the cost of which is reimbursed to the UK by the member state which provides the individual’s insurance.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-31T08:21:14.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753651/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753651/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-18","Health Services: Reciprocal Arrangements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 49 of his Department's policy paper entitled Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what healthcare arrangements have been set out in EU Regulations and domestic law for UK nationals and EU citizens that the Government will seek to protect and guarantee.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","5866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753652","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-26","<p>We have been clear that we expect the EU to ensure that life for UK nationals in the EU continues much as it does now, in the same way that we are doing for EU nationals in the UK. This must therefore include the ability to work in one Member State but live in another, for those to whom this applies.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T12:09:35.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753652/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753652/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-18","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 6 of his Department's policy paper entitled Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what rights the Government will seek to guarantee for UK nationals who work in one EU Member State but live in another EU Member State or the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","5867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753653","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-26","<p>We have published a <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/631038/Joint_technical_note_on_the_comparison_of_EU-UK_positions_on_citizens__rights.pdf" target="_blank">joint technical note</a>, with the EU, on the comparison of UK and EU positions on citizens’ rights. There is much common ground between the two positions, a clearer understanding on the detail of the positions, and significant convergence on the key issues that really matter to citizens.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T12:11:45.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753653/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753653/answer","Joint_technical_note_on_the_comparison_of_EU-UK_positions_on_citizens__rights.pdf","Joint_technical_note_on_the_comparison_of_EU-UK_positions_on_citizens__rights.pdf","UK-EU joint technical note on citizen's rights","UK-EU joint technical note on citizen's rights","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753653/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-18","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 13 July 2017 to Question 3786, what assessment he has made of the level of rights protection offered to UK citizens in other EU Member States as proposed in the Brexit: negotiating directives issued on 22 May 2017 by the European Council, compared with the offer outlined in his Department's policy paper, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","5868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753654","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-07-26","<p>The Department has regular conversations with officials and Ministers from other governmental departments about a range of policy issues arising from EU exit. With regards to the Erasmus+ programme, the Government recognises the value of international exchange and collaboration in education as part of our vision for the UK as a global nation.</p><p>There may be European programmes in which we wish to continue to participate after we exit. This will be considered as part of ongoing negotiations with the European Union.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T12:07:14.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753654/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753654/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-07-18","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Education on the future of the UK's participation in the Erasmus scheme.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","5908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753655","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-07-26","<p>The Government recognises the value of international exchange and collaboration in education as part of our vision for the UK as a global nation. There may be European programmes in which we wish to continue to participate after we exit. This will be considered as part of ongoing negotiations with the European Union.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T09:34:06.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753655/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753655/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-07-18","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with his counterparts on the future of the UK's participation in the Erasmus scheme.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","5907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753656","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-26","<p>Family members of eligible EU citizens (either EU citizens or non-EU nationals) who are resident in the UK before exit will be eligible to apply for settled status after five years, irrespective of the specified date.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T16:49:16.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753656/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753656/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753656/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-18","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 2017 to Question 3557, whether (a) EU and (b) non-EU family members who join eligible EU citizens before (i) the specified date and (ii) the UK leaves the EU will be able to apply for settled status after five years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","5875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753657","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-26","<p>Those who have been living in the UK for five years before the specified date and want to continue to make the UK their home will be able to apply for settled status to stay indefinitely after we exit.</p><p>Those who have already lived in the UK for over five years and hold permanent residence status under EU law, but were not present at the time of the specified date, will still be eligible for settled status if that absence was less than two consecutive years.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T15:28:04.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753657/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753657/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-18","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 13 July 2017 to Question 3560, whether non-UK EU nationals who have previously lived in the UK but have been absent for more than two consecutive years will have the right to move back to the UK to start accruing years of residence and be eligible for settled status.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","5921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753658","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-26","<p>As set out in our policy paper of 26 June, we want to provide as much certainty as possible to the three million EU citizens in the UK and the one million UK nationals in the EU, and for their lives to continue broadly as they do now. The precise rules around family reunion will be a matter for negotiations.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T12:08:16.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753658/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753658/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753658/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-18","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 2017 to Question 3557, if during the negotiations on the UK's exit from the EU, he will seek for UK citizens in the EU after the specified date to have the right to bring their family members into the country of residence in accordance with current EU rules.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","5920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753659","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-26","<p>The contract referred to in the answer to Question 3956 was for the provision of transport. The contracted company advised that they were unable to fully meet the requirements set out by the Department and the Department was therefore able to exit the arrangement without charge.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-26T16:50:26.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753659/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753659/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-18","Department for Exiting the European Union: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 18 July 2017 to Question 3956, on procurement, which contract was cancelled; and what the status was of that contract at cancellation.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","5941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753661","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>Figures for the department's overall carbon emissions are published annually in the Cabinet Office's Annual Report &amp; Accounts. Carbon emissions from the Cabinet Office estate are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2015 - 5,950.34 Tonnes of CO2e</p><p>2016 - 5,092.77 Tonnes of CO2e</p><p>2017 (Jan-Mar) - 1425.5 Tonnes of CO2e</p><p> </p><p>Total CO2e emissions = 12468.61</p><p> </p><p>The Cabinet Office is fully committed to meeting the Government's Greening Government Commitments (GGC). The GGC departmental commitment is to reduce carbon emissions from a 2009/10 baseline by 35% by 2020; to date the department has achieved a reduction of over 50% in its overall emissions reductions.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-05T13:36:58.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753661/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753661/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-18","Cabinet Office: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the level of carbon emissions from his Department's buildings in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","5880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753662","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The overall amount spent on external consultancy by the Cabinet Office is published in the Cabinet Office Annual Report and Accounts available on page 52 on the below link. The Crown Commercial Service executive agency hold this information in their own accounts, which are available online.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2015-to-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>Accounts for 2016-17 will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-05T13:28:11.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753662/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753662/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-18","Cabinet Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much (a) his Department and (b) each (i) non-departmental public body and (ii) executive agency for which his Department is responsible spent on external consultants and advisers in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","5881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753663","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and therefore can only be provided at disproportionate costs.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-05T13:02:27.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753663/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753663/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-18","Cabinet Office: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much was spent on advertising by (a) his Department and (b) each of its (i) non-departmental public bodies and (ii) executive agencies in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","5882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753664","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-25","<p>The Government’s view is that electoral fraud is unacceptable on any level. Sir Eric Pickles’ review made a number of recommendations for strengthening the integrity of the electoral process, including requiring voters to provide a form of identification at polling stations before voting. In line with the manifesto commitment, the Government plans to run pilot schemes in a number of local authority areas in 2018 that will test the requirement for voters to present ID before voting. Pilots will help to identify the best way of administering this new requirement.</p><p>The Government is considering the way forward on the other recommendations made by Sir Eric Pickles, and will continue to consider how to improve the integrity of electoral processes more generally.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-25T15:39:24.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753664/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753664/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-18","Elections: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government has taken to implement the recommendations of Sir Eric Pickles' review of electoral fraud entitled Securing the ballot.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","5952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753665","Department of Health","false","2017-07-21","<p>We will work to address the challenges of social care for our ageing population, bringing forward proposals for consultation to build widespread support.</p><p> </p><p>We will provide further details on the next steps on social care in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to listening to people’s views on how to reform the social care system, to ensure it is sustainable for current and future generations and that the quality of care improves. Further information on this will be made available shortly.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-21T12:43:17.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753665/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753665/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-18","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to publish details of the scope of the planned consultation on social care.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","5983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753666","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-25","<p>Self-employed people currently pay two types of National Insurance contributions (NICs): Class 2 and Class 4. The government has no current plans to change NICs beyond those already announced.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-25T09:47:00.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753666/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753666/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-18","National Insurance Contributions: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to his oral contribution of 18 July 2017, on income tax and national insurance, what plans he has to change national insurance for self-employed people.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","5982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753667","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-24","<p>The UK has led international action to enhance tax transparency. This included initiating the international work on country-by-country reporting during its G8 Presidency in 2013, and being the first country to commit to implement the OECD model for country-by country reporting with legislation in the 2015 Finance Act.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes a multilateral approach to public country-by-country reporting would help ensure effective implementation. The UK has raised public country-by-country reporting with international partners and the Government will continue to engage with our international partners, including at EU level, on this issue.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","5915","2017-07-24T11:44:00.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753667/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753667/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-18","Taxation: Multinational Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress he has made on reaching a multilateral agreement under which the UK will adopt public country-by-country reporting.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","5916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753668","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-24","<p>The UK has led international action to enhance tax transparency. This included initiating the international work on country-by-country reporting during its G8 Presidency in 2013, and being the first country to commit to implement the OECD model for country-by country reporting with legislation in the 2015 Finance Act.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes a multilateral approach to public country-by-country reporting would help ensure effective implementation. The UK has raised public country-by-country reporting with international partners and the Government will continue to engage with our international partners, including at EU level, on this issue.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","5916","2017-07-24T11:44:00.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753668/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753668/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-18","Taxation: Multinational Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions the Government had at the June 2017 G20 summit on a multilateral agreement on public country-by-country reporting.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","5915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753669","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-05","<p>Over recent years, policies to help with the cost of living such as the rise in the personal allowance, worth £1,000 to a basic-rate taxpayer, have also benefited millions of public sector workers.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-05T07:55:34.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753669/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753669/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-18","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the public sector pay cap on living standards for public sector workers.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","5884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753670","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-24","<p>I refer the honourable gentlemen to my <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=QuestionsWithAnswersOnly&amp;house=commons&amp;uin=2583" target="_blank">written answer</a> on 11 July 2017, (UIN 2583) which refers to the to the location principles HMRC used to select its regional centres.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst accepting there may be an impact on locations it is leaving, HMRC is committed to maximising tax revenue, increasing compliance and reducing the tax gap while delivering best value to the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>However, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) expects the economic impact on locations it is leaving to be limited as those taking up posts in a regional centre will continue their normal activities where they live and the office accommodation HMRC vacates is likely to be re-let or redeveloped by the landlords.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-24T10:43:09.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753670/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753670/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-18","Revenue and Customs: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, to what extent HM Revenue and Customs took account of local labour market conditions and regional economic prospects when it decided to close many of its existing offices and move to regional centres.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","5960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753671","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-24","<p>Access to personal tax and National Insurance records is strictly controlled. Staff are not permitted to use HMRC systems to access their own tax records.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-24T10:51:32.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753671/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753671/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-18","Taxation: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether HM Revenue and Customs' employees are permitted to access their own personal tax account when using their work computer.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","5961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753672","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-24","<p>The HMRC Gender Pay Gap is available online at the government website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-gender-pay-gap-2015/hm-revenue-and-customs-gender-pay-gap-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-gender-pay-gap-2015/hm-revenue-and-customs-gender-pay-gap-2015</a></p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-24T10:42:17.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753672/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753672/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-18","Revenue and Customs: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the gender pay gap is within HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","5964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753673","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-26","<p>Government departments have been analysing the UK statute book and directly applicable EU law in areas of responsibility to enable an assessment of the scale of the changes needed. This is likely to include the repeal, but also the amendment, of provisions in Acts but we are not in a position to give a sense of scale at this time. <br> <br> In the Government White Paper on the Repeal Bill, published on 30 March 2017, we estimated around 800-1,000 EU-exit Statutory Instruments will be required.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-07-26T10:54:44.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753673/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753673/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-18","Department for Communities and Local Government: European Union (Withdrawal) Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the potential number of Acts or parts of Acts that will be subject to repeal as a result of provisions in the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","5988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753674","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Department does not record incidences of rat and mice infestation in England.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-07-24T11:01:40.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753674/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753674/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-18","Rodents: Pest Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many incidences of rat and mice infestation were recorded in England by his Department in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","5967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753675","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-26","<p>Government departments have been analysing the United Kingdom statute book and directly applicable European Union law in their areas of responsibility to enable an assessment of the scale of the changes needed. This is likely to include the repeal, but also the amendment, of provisions in Acts but we are not in a position to give a sense of scale at this time.</p><p> </p><p>In the Government White Paper on the Repeal Bill Legislating for the UK’s withdrawal from the EU, published on 30 March 2017, we estimated around 800-1,000 EU-exit related Statutory Instruments will be required.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-26T10:36:18.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753675/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753675/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-18","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: European Union (Withdrawal) Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate her Department has made of the potential number of Acts or parts of Acts that will be subject to repeal as a result of provisions in the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","5987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753676","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-25","<p>As the Review of Full Time Social Action by Young People is independent of government, evidence gathering is a matter for the Chair. A call for evidence will be launched shortly and the panel will also consult with key stakeholders, including young people.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-25T09:05:51.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753676/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753676/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-18","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department plans to take to publicise the independent review of full-time social action by young people in order to maximise participation in evidence gathering.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","5918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753677","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-26","<p>We continue to work with partners across the international community to press for key steps towards multilateral disarmament, including the entry into force of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty and successful negotiations on a Fissile Material Cut-Off Treaty in the Conference on Disarmament. There have been significant reductions in global warhead numbers since the late 1970s; the UK has reduced our nuclear forces by over half since that date.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-26T11:16:58.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753677/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753677/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-18","Nuclear Disarmament","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to his Department's statement of 8 July on the outcome of the United Nations' Nuclear Weapons Ban treaty, which multilateral nuclear disarmament negotiations using a step-by-step approach the UK is currently engaged in; and how many nuclear warheads have been removed from deployment as a result of such negotiations since the Nuclear Non-Proliferation treaty.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","5947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753678","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-26","<p>The treaty prohibiting nuclear weapons risks weakening the consensus around the near-universal Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT), which has played an unparalleled role in curtailing the nuclear arms race. The UK is working with international partners to make progress on the step-by-step approach to nuclear disarmament, including the entry into force of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty and negotiating a Fissile Material Cut-Off Treaty in the Conference on Disarmament. The treaty prohibiting nuclear weapons does not take account of the complex challenges which must be overcome to achieve multilateral nuclear disarmament. The UK is committed to the long term goal of a world without nuclear weapons, in line with the NPT. We believe that productive results on nuclear disarmament can only be achieved through a consensus-based approach that takes into account the wider global security context.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-26T11:07:09.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753678/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753678/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-18","Nuclear Disarmament","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the joint statement by the UK, US and France of 7 July 2017 on the adoption of a treaty banning nuclear weapons, how the ban treaty risks undermining the existing international security architecture; and how the Government has promoted the effectiveness of Article 6 of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty on nuclear disarmament.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","5948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753679","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-26","<p>The safety and security of the defence estate continues to be of the utmost importance. There are many ways this is achieved, including the vital role provided by the Ministry of Defence Police.</p><p>Discussions are ongoing across the Department in order to ensure that our policing resources are deployed where they are most needed. We continue to fully safeguard all of our sites and would never contemplate changes that would place these in jeopardy. Consultation with the Defence Police Federation will take place in the normal manner.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","5958","2017-07-26T10:36:19.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753679/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753679/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-18","Ministry of Defence Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what consultations his Department conducted before the decision was taken to reduce the size of the Ministry of Defence Police's officer complement; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","5959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753680","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-26","<p>The safety and security of the defence estate continues to be of the utmost importance. There are many ways this is achieved, including the vital role provided by the Ministry of Defence Police.</p><p>Discussions are ongoing across the Department in order to ensure that our policing resources are deployed where they are most needed. We continue to fully safeguard all of our sites and would never contemplate changes that would place these in jeopardy. Consultation with the Defence Police Federation will take place in the normal manner.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","5959","2017-07-26T10:36:19.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753680/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753680/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-18","Ministry of Defence Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the effect of planned reductions to the Ministry of Defence Police's officer complement on the security of the defence estate.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","5958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753681","Department for Education","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) Budget for the years 2017 – 2020:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£19.3m</p></td><td><p>£18.3m</p></td><td><p>£17.4m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The EHRC has, and will continue to receive sufficient funds to enable it to fulfil its statutory functions.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-24T18:15:57.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753681/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753681/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753681/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-18","Equality and Human Rights Commission: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what budget has been allocated to the Equality and Human Rights Commission for (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19 and (c) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","5963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753682","Department for Education","false","2017-07-24","<p>As the Secretary of State set out in her statement on 17 July 2017, we will make £315 million savings from the healthy pupils capital programme, reflecting reductions in the forecast revenue from the soft drinks industry levy, and release £280 million in savings from our free schools programme by working more efficiently to deliver our ambitious programme. This includes working more collaboratively with local authorities to provide free schools to meet basic need</p><p>We will identify the rest of the savings from efficiencies across the rest of the Department’s budget as we believe strongly that this funding is most valuable in the hands of head teachers and principals. The Secretary of State has asked the Department to conduct an internal exercise to identify these efficiencies without impacting on the delivery of our key priorities. We will say more about the outcome of this exercise in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-24T18:19:43.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753682/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753682/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-18","Schools: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to her oral statement of 17 June 2017 on school funding, Official Report, column 568, by what process she will identify programmes for further efficiency savings; and when she plans to complete that process.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","5951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753683","Department for Education","false","2017-07-25","<p>Government departments have been analysing the UK statute book and directly applicable EU law in their areas of responsibility to enable an assessment of the scale of the changes needed. This is likely to include the repeal, but also the amendment, of provisions in Acts but we are not in a position to give a sense of scale at this time.</p><p> </p><p>In the Government White Paper on the Repeal Bill [‘Legislating for the United Kingdom’s withdrawal from the European Union’], published on 30 March 2017, we estimated around 800 - 1,000 EU-exit related Statutory Instruments will be required.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-25T17:49:46.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753683/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753683/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-18","Department for Education: European Union (Withdrawal) Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the potential number of Acts or parts of Acts that will be subject to repeal as a result of provisions in the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","5985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753684","Department for Education","false","2017-07-25","<p>The early years funding allocation for South Tyneside local authority can be found here for the following financial years:</p><p>2013-14:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-2013-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-2013-to-2014</a></p><p>2014-15:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-2014-to-2015</a></p><p>2015-16:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2015-to-2016</a></p><p>2016-17:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2016-to-2017</a></p><p>2017-18 – First year under Early Years National Funding Formula (provisional allocation):</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018</a></p><p>Prior to 2013-14, early years’ local authority funding allocations were not separately identified within the Dedicated Schools Grant (DSG). Instead, they were part of the total DSG allocated to each local authority. Early years allocations prior to 2013-14 are not therefore available.</p><p>Funding allocations for 2018-19 and 2019-20 will be announced in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-25T17:51:59.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753684/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753684/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-18","Pre-school Education: South Tyneside","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding has been made available to South Tyneside local authority for early years provision in each of the last seven years; and how much funding is being made available to South Tyneside local authority for early years provision under her Department's new early years national funding formula in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","5962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753685","Department for Education","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Post-16 Skills Plan set out our plan to reform technical education including the introduction of 15 new technical routes to skilled employment, new college-based training programmes (T Levels) based on employer-designed standards, and high quality T Level work placements.</p><p>Delivering these reforms will be transformational; and we are determined to ensure they are a success and achieve their overall aims: to transform technical education and create a high quality system that delivers the skills, knowledge and behaviours that employers and the country need.</p><p>The only way to deliver this challenge successfully is through genuine partnership between government, business experts/leaders and education professionals.</p><p>My officials have now carried out extensive testing of the current delivery plans, including in relation to work placement provision, in discussion with employers, providers and awarding organisations. Following that assessment, we have concluded that we will deliver a small number of T levels from September 2020, with all routes available as planned in September 2022.</p><p>Over the summer, we will continue to refine and develop our plans working with business and the providers, and we will provide an update on progress in the autumn.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-20T15:02:19.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753685/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753685/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-18","Vocational Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the timetable is for delivery of the first T-levels.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Pow","Taunton Deane","Rebecca Pow","5990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753686","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-26","<p>Government departments have been analysing the UK statute book and directly applicable EU law in their areas of responsibility to enable an assessment of the scale of the changes needed. This is likely to include the repeal, but also the amendment, of provisions in Acts but we are not in a position to give a sense of scale at this time.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In the Government White Paper on the Repeal Bill [‘Legislating for the United Kingdom’s withdrawal from the European Union’], published on 30 March 2017, we estimated around 800 - 1,000 EU-exit related Statutory Instruments will be required for the whole of Government.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-07-26T10:42:57.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753686/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753686/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-18","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: European Union (Withdrawal) Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the potential number of Acts or parts of Acts that will be subject to repeal as a result of provisions in the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","5986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753687","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>Tackling the illegal wildlife trade and bringing an end to elephant poaching is a priority for this government.</p><p> </p><p>We are taking practical action to tackle the illegal wildlife trade, particularly through the Illegal Wildlife Trade Challenge Fund. Many projects funded through the challenge fund work to protect elephants from poaching. Defra also funds the British Army training for park ranges in key African countries. UK law enforcement agencies are active around the world, sharing expertise and intelligence to help tackle poaching and trafficking.</p><p> </p><p>Here in the UK there are strict rules controlling the sale of ivory. This is backed up by robust enforcement from Border Force and the National Wildlife Crime Unit. The UK prohibits all commercial trade in raw ivory of any age, going further than the EU regulations. We are considering options for taking further action to address the UK ivory market.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-05T10:32:46.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753687/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753687/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-18","Elephants: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to protect elephants against the illegal wildlife trade.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","5888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753688","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>We are using the UK’s growing reputation for high quality food and drink, with high standards of animal welfare, traceability and sustainability to increase demand for our great British products.</p><p> </p><p>We are opening up public procurement to more small and medium sized enterprises (SMEs) and local producers. We are raising the profile and reputation of British food and drink overseas through the Food is GREAT campaign. Defra and DIT are also opening new markets and supporting exports in priority markets such as China, USA and India.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-05T10:10:07.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753688/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753688/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-18","Food: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to promote the sale (a) in the UK and (b) globally of food produced in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","5887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753689","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-24","<p>Defra does not hold information in relation to a recent estimate of the number of urban seagulls.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-07-24T11:07:50.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753689/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753689/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-18","Seagulls: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent estimate he has made of the urban seagull population in England.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","5968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753690","Department of Health","false","2017-07-21","<p>The information requested is in the table below, which shows a count of finished admission episodes with a primary diagnosis for rickets, scabies and tuberculosis in England from 2006-07 to 2015-16.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Scabies</p></td><td><p>Rickets</p></td><td><p>Tuberculosis</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>209</p></td><td><p>91</p></td><td><p>4,371</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>189</p></td><td><p>83</p></td><td><p>4,366</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>192</p></td><td><p>95</p></td><td><p>4,546</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>157</p></td><td><p>66</p></td><td><p>4,096</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>145</p></td><td><p>66</p></td><td><p>4,417</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>148</p></td><td><p>74</p></td><td><p>4,352</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>141</p></td><td><p>65</p></td><td><p>4,136</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>141</p></td><td><p>39</p></td><td><p>3,740</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>139</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>3,013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>118</p></td><td><p>48</p></td><td><p>2,912</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>Source: Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-07-21T13:29:42.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753690/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753690/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-18","Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many incidences of (a) rickets, (b) scabies and (c) tuberculosis there were in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","5969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753691","Department of Health","false","2017-07-24","<p>Health Education England (HEE) has already increased to 50% the proportion of doctors undertaking a four month psychiatry post during their foundation programme training and the Royal College of Psychiatry will complete the review of this expansion with a view to HEE commissioning a further expansion from 2019.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this, HEE is to ensure that from 2018 all foundation programme doctors not undertaking the four month training post will be required to complete a two week ‘taster’ attachment in psychiatry.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-24T10:44:30.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753691/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753691/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-18","Doctors: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether it is the Government's policy to ensure that all medical trainees gain experience working in mental health disciplines.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","5992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753692","Department of Health","false","2017-07-21","<p>The Department is working very closely with the Department for Education in drawing up the Green Paper for children’s and young people’s mental health. We expect to publish the paper before the end of the year.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-21T12:44:47.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753692/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753692/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-18","Mental Health Services: Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Education on including proposals for the better integration of child and adolescent mental health services with schools, in the proposed Green Paper on children and young people's mental health.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","5993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753693","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-25","<p>Earlier this year, the Prime Minister announced the first steps in our plan to transform the way we deal with mental health problems at every stage of a person’s life. A range of new measures were announced, including two new reviews. In addition, the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health and NHS England’s Implementation Plan sets out a series of actions to prevent mental ill health, improve services and reduce stigma.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-25T13:54:45.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753693/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753693/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-18","Unemployed People: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to tackle the increase in mental health illness among unemployed people as highlighted in the findings of the recent report by the UK Council for Pyschotherapy.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","5994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753694","Department of Health","false","2017-07-21","<p>The information is not published in the format requested. Anxiety and depression diagnoses are not broken down by occupation.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-21T12:50:56.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753694/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753694/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-18","Mental Illness: Unemployed People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the number of unemployed people diagnosed with (a) anxiety and (b) depression in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","5996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753695","Department of Health","false","2017-07-24","<p>Over recent months the National Health Service has seen record numbers of doctors employed. Since May 2010 the numbers of doctors has increased by almost 11,700.</p><p> </p><p>Responsibility for staffing levels rests with individual NHS trusts and their boards who are best placed to decide how many staff they need to provide a given service, taking into account skill mix, efficiency and the needs of their local population.</p><p> </p><p>By increasing the number of medical school places in England by 1,500 we are ensuring the right number of doctors are trained so that the NHS can continue to deliver safe, compassionate and effective care well into the future.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","5872","2017-07-24T10:47:59.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753695/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753695/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-18","University Hospitals Coventry and Warwickshire NHS Trust: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the level of vacancies for medical staff at University Hospitals Coventry and Warwickshire NHS Trust; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","5874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753696","Department of Health","false","2017-07-25","<p>Government departments have been analysing the United Kingdom statute book and directly applicable European Union law in their areas of responsibility to enable an assessment of the scale of the changes needed. This is likely to include the repeal, but also the amendment, of provisions in Acts but we are not in a position to give a sense of scale at this time.</p><p> </p><p>In the Government White Paper on the Repeal Bill Legislating for the UK’s withdrawal from the EU, published on 30 March 2017, we estimated around 800 - 1,000 EU-exit related Statutory Instruments will be required.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-25T09:35:35.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753696/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753696/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-18","Department of Health: European Union (Withdrawal) Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the potential number of Acts or parts of Acts that will be subject to repeal as a result of provisions in the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","5989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753697","Department of Health","false","2017-07-21","<p>We will work to address the challenges of social care for our ageing population, bringing forward proposals for consultation to build widespread support.</p><p> </p><p>The Government wants to hear a range of views from members of the public, representative groups, commissioners, providers, those using services and carers as its shapes its thinking.</p><p> </p><p>This is why we have set out our intention to consult and will set out more detail shortly.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-21T12:42:00.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753697/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753697/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-18","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make it his policy to consult with (a) disabled people, (b) carers and (c) social care providers during the planned consultation on social care.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","5984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753698","Home Office","false","2017-07-25","<p>The Immigration Skills Charge (ISC), introduced on 6 April, is a charge paid by employers, rather than by migrant workers themselves. It applies to the recruitment of non-EEA nationals being sponsored under the Tier 2 (General) and (Intra Company Transfer) categories.</p><p>The charge is applied based on the level of the job, not on the qualifications held by the migrant. Psychiatrists are not considered to be a PhD-level occupation, so employers will normally need to pay the charge.</p><p>Employers will not need to pay the charge, however, if they are sponsoring a psychiatrist who is switching from Tier 4, the student route, or who was originally sponsored in Tier 2 before 6 April 2017.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-25T14:51:14.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753698/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753698/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Psychiatry: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether NHS psychiatrists who do not have a PhD and are on a Tier 2 visa will be affected by the International Skills Charge.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","5991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753699","Home Office","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Home Office collects information on the number of hate crimes recorded by the police. Information is not held on how many of these hate crimes involved a corrosive substance.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of hate crimes recorded by the police is published on an annual basis in the statistical bulletin Hate Crime, England and Wales, 2015/16, available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/hate-crime-england-and-wales-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/hate-crime-england-and-wales-2015-to-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>This Government is committed to tackling hate crime. The UK has a strong legislative framework to tackle hate crime. We are working across Government with police, (including National Community Tensions Team), the Crown Prosecution Service and community partners to send out a clear message that hate crime will not be tolerated and we will vigorously pursue and prosecute those who commit these crimes.</p><p> </p><p>We have also announced a cross Government action plan to tackle the use of acid and other corrosives in violent attacks which includes improving police recording and reporting of offences.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-24T16:15:29.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753699/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753699/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Hate Crime: Corrosive Substances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many attacks involving a corrosive substance were treated as a hate crime in (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","5950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753700","Home Office","false","2017-07-24","<p>All asylum seekers whose applications have been fully determined and have exhausted their appeal rights are required to leave the UK as soon as possible. Where failed asylum seekers who would otherwise be destitute are unable to leave the UK due to circumstances beyond their control they can continue to be supported until the barrier to their return is removed. The Home Office publishes quarterly figures on the number of asylum seekers in receipt of support, including under Section 4 of the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999, in table as_18q in volume 4 of the Asylum data tables. These are available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2017/list-of-tables#asylum" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2017/list-of-tables#asylum</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-24T13:21:37.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753700/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753700/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Asylum: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many refused asylum seekers have been made homeless in (a) the UK and (b) Liverpool for each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","5957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753701","Home Office","false","2017-07-26","<p>This information is not collated centrally. This is an operational matter for individual forces.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","5972","2017-07-26T14:01:24.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753701/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753701/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Police: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how often tasking meetings were held by the Police in each London borough in (a) 2010 and (b) 2016.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","5971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753702","Home Office","false","2017-07-26","<p>This information is not collated centrally. This is an operational matter for individual forces.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","5971","2017-07-26T14:01:24.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753702/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753702/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the frequency was of Police tasking meetings in each Police area in England and Wales in (a) 2010 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","5972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753703","Home Office","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes data annually on the number of officers primarily employed in Counter Terrorism/Special Branch roles as part of the <em>Police workforce, England and Wales </em>statistical bulletin. This can be accessed at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Data as at 31 March 2016 can be found in Table F4 of the police workforce statistics published in July 2016 at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/544954/police-workforce-tabs-jul16.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/544954/police-workforce-tabs-jul16.ods</a></p><p> </p><p>These data do not include all officers supporting counter-terrorism work and excludes many of those posts funded separately by the Counter-Terrorism Policing Grant and those in some national counter-terrorism functions. For reasons of national security, we do not publish the number or location of posts funded by the Counter-Terrorism Policing Grant. The published figures do not, therefore, reflect the total number of officers assigned to counter-terrorism policing.</p><p> </p><p>Previous data were collected under a different framework, with different definitions. Therefore, data prior to 31 March 2015 are not directly comparable with later years. Although some functions may appear to be similar between the two frameworks, there are often differences in definitions, and so any attempts to compare across the two should be done with caution. Data under the old framework have been published since 2012, and can be found in the supplementary data tables of the relevant police workforce publications via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales</a></p><p> </p><p>The Home Office does not collect data on the primary functions of police officers at the level (London borough) requested, only at the police force area level.</p><p> </p><p>Any comparisons at force level should be made with care due to collaboration arrangements between forces for particular functions. Additionally, police functions data are often affected by re-structuring within police forces. Therefore comparisons over time for specific functions should be made with care.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace","5974","2017-07-24T16:09:21.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753703/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753703/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Counter-terrorism: Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many counter-terrorism liaison officers were in post in each Police area in England and Wales in 2010.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","5973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753704","Home Office","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes data annually on the number of officers primarily employed in Counter Terrorism/Special Branch roles as part of the <em>Police workforce, England and Wales </em>statistical bulletin. This can be accessed at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Data as at 31 March 2016 can be found in Table F4 of the police workforce statistics published in July 2016 at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/544954/police-workforce-tabs-jul16.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/544954/police-workforce-tabs-jul16.ods</a></p><p> </p><p>These data do not include all officers supporting counter-terrorism work and excludes many of those posts funded separately by the Counter-Terrorism Policing Grant and those in some national counter-terrorism functions. For reasons of national security, we do not publish the number or location of posts funded by the Counter-Terrorism Policing Grant. The published figures do not, therefore, reflect the total number of officers assigned to counter-terrorism policing.</p><p> </p><p>Previous data were collected under a different framework, with different definitions. Therefore, data prior to 31 March 2015 are not directly comparable with later years. Although some functions may appear to be similar between the two frameworks, there are often differences in definitions, and so any attempts to compare across the two should be done with caution. Data under the old framework have been published since 2012, and can be found in the supplementary data tables of the relevant police workforce publications via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales</a></p><p> </p><p>The Home Office does not collect data on the primary functions of police officers at the level (London borough) requested, only at the police force area level.</p><p> </p><p>Any comparisons at force level should be made with care due to collaboration arrangements between forces for particular functions. Additionally, police functions data are often affected by re-structuring within police forces. Therefore comparisons over time for specific functions should be made with care.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace","5973","2017-07-24T16:09:21.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753704/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753704/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Counter-terrorism: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many counter-terrorism liaison officers were in post in each London Borough in (a) 2010 and (b) 2016.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","5974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753705","Home Office","false","2017-07-26","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes data on the number of officers primarily employed in Neighbourhood Policing/Safer Neighbourhood roles by police force area. However, the Home Office does not hold data on the number of Safer Neighbourhood teams, only on the number of full-time equivalent officers under their primary function.</p><p> </p><p>The number of full time equivalent police officers in each police force (and specifically in the Metropolitan Police), primarily employed in Neighbourhood Policing/Safer Neighbourhood roles, can be found in the data tables published alongside the annual ‘Police workforce, England and Wales’ statistical bulletins, which can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales</a></p><p> </p><p>Data as at 31 March 2017 can be found in Table F1 of the accompanying tables of the police workforce statistics, published on 20 July 2017, here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>Previous data were collected under a different framework, with different definitions. Therefore, data prior to 31 March 2015 are not directly comparable with later years. Although some functions may appear to be similar between the two, there are often differences in definitions, and so any attempts to compare across the two frameworks should be done with caution. Data under the old framework have been published since 2012, and can be found in the supplementary data tables of the relevant police workforce publications via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales</a></p><p> </p><p>Officers with multiple responsibilities or designations are recorded under their primary function. The data do not therefore provide a complete picture of all officers assigned to neighbourhood policing functions. A more reliable measure is the number of officers employed in ‘Local policing’ roles, which includes both neighbourhood and response functions. This measure is available for 2015 and 2016, but not for previous years where a different framework was used.</p><p> </p><p>Any comparisons at force level should be made with care due to collaboration arrangements between forces for particular functions. Additionally, police functions data are often affected by re-structuring within police forces. Therefore comparisons over time for specific functions should be made with care.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office does not collect data at the London borough or at the ward level. Data as at 31 January, or broken down by rank, are also not available.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on duties and deployments are matters for Chief Constables and the directly accountable Police and Crime Commissioners for each local area.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government believes in local policing, accountable to local communities. That is why we abolished all central Government targets and put local people in charge by introducing directly elected police and crime commissioners.</p><p> </p><p>Police and Crime Commissioners, the elected mayors in London and Manchester and local forces are transforming the way in which they deploy operational resources to meet local circumstances and priorities and adapt to the changing crime threat. The distinction between Neighbourhoods and response teams is no longer clear cut as forces transform the way in which they deploy operational resources and evolve roles to meet local circumstances and priorities, and adapt to the changing crime threat.</p><p> </p><p>The freedom to exercise discretion and flexibility has resulted in a range of local policing approaches. At least 33 forces have introduced significant changes, including merging neighbourhoods and response functions; or, for example, in Durham where safeguarding teams have been bought together with Neighbourhoods teams.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","5772 ; 5773 ; 5774 ; 5775 ; 5776 ; 5777 ; 5778 ; 5779","2017-07-26T14:07:15.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753705/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753705/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Safer Neighbourhood Teams","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the main duties are of Safer Neighbourhood teams.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","5975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753706","Home Office","false","2017-07-26","<p>Acid and other corrosive attacks resulting in injury are included in Office for National Statistics published statistics within the relevant offence, such as assault with injury or assault with intent to cause serious harm.</p><p>Indicative figures from the National Police Chiefs’ Council suggest that 408 acid or corrosive attacks were carried out in the six months up to April 2017, based on returns from 39 police forces in England and Wales. These figures must be treated with caution, as they are not official statistics. We have also announced a cross Government action plan to tackle the use of acid and other corrosives in violent attacks which includes improving police recording and reporting of offences.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-26T13:55:03.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753706/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753706/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-18","Crimes of Violence: Corrosive Substances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the recorded number of (a) attackers and (b) victims of an incident involving a corrosive substance was by gender in (i) 2015, (ii) 2016 and (iii) 2017.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","5949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753707","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-26","<p>Child sexual abuse is abhorrent, and victims can apply for taxpayer-funded compensation awards through the Criminal Injuries Compensation Scheme (the Scheme).</p><p> </p><p>The Scheme is made by the Secretary of State under the Criminal Injuries Compensation Act 1995 having been approved by each House of Parliament. The Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority (CICA) administers the Scheme and decides all claims independently of ministers and Parliament. The CICA sets guidelines to assist them in administering the Scheme.</p><p>The CICA guidelines are intended to make sure that controlling and abusive behaviour is taken into account when handling compensation applications for child sexual abuse. The CICA are urgently reviewing their guidelines to ensure they are robust enough to deal with cases where grooming may be a factor.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","5954","2017-07-26T14:45:22.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753707/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753707/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-18","Criminal Injuries Compensation: Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will update the guidance to the Criminal Injuries Compensation Scheme so that the governing rules are in line with the law and state that a child under 16 years cannot consent to sexual activity.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","5953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753708","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-26","<p>Child sexual abuse is abhorrent, and victims can apply for taxpayer-funded compensation awards through the Criminal Injuries Compensation Scheme (the Scheme).</p><p> </p><p>The Scheme is made by the Secretary of State under the Criminal Injuries Compensation Act 1995 having been approved by each House of Parliament. The Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority (CICA) administers the Scheme and decides all claims independently of ministers and Parliament. The CICA sets guidelines to assist them in administering the Scheme.</p><p>The CICA guidelines are intended to make sure that controlling and abusive behaviour is taken into account when handling compensation applications for child sexual abuse. The CICA are urgently reviewing their guidelines to ensure they are robust enough to deal with cases where grooming may be a factor.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","5953","2017-07-26T14:45:22.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753708/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753708/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-18","Criminal Injuries Compensation: Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will update the guidance to the Criminal Injuries Compensation Scheme so that the governing rules do not discriminate against a child who has been coerced into criminal activity as a result of grooming.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","5954"
